The paper deals with a problem in phylogenetics, which is a subfield of biology that uses computational methods to study evolutionary relationships among organisms. The problem is related to the compatibility of unrooted phylogenetic trees, which is a well-studied problem in computer science. The paper uses graph-theoretic techniques to study the problem and shows that the treewidth of an auxiliary structure known as the display graph is a key parameter in determining the compatibility of the input trees. Therefore, the paper is likely to be relevant to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CG (Computational Geometry), cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Among these, cs.DM and cs.DS are the most likely categories, as the paper deals with graph theory and algorithmic techniques for solving a combinatorial problem.
